Albrecht,

I don&#39;t think that will work very well, since reactor time integration 
must be restarted after you modify the gas composition.  In general, 
any manual modification of the state of a reactor should be avoided.

Here&#39;s a better approach:  define a reaction mechanism of reversible 
reactions that connect all of the species.  These do not need to be 
elementary reactions.  For example, you could  write formation 
reactions for each species from a set of &#39;constituents&#39; (perhaps major 
species, or even the atomic vapor species - e.g. C + 4H &lt;=&gt; CH4).  Give 
each reaction a sufficiently large rate coefficient so that it is fast 
compared to the time scales of interest.  Then simply use this 
mechanism in your reactor. You should find that the results are 
independent of the rate constants chosen, as long as they are all fast 
enough.  You can check that the rates are fast enough by looking at the 
characteristic destruction times (concentration / molar destruction 
rate).

Dave


